:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In England a Electrician has to register with a Scheme so when he or she complete</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">s certification for the local planning at a cost of £1.90p yet if an electrician who is not scheme registered want to submit certification then its £190.00p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt"> So in my view this does not comply with the European Free Trade Act and discriminates against a le</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">gally qualified insured electrician.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">As for Part P well what you were not told was that the Schemes to get more revenue run 6 week courses to train individuals to be domestic electricians good grief it took me 4 years to get to Electrician grade than a fur</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ther 2 to get to Approved status 6 years in total. As for the Scheme policing the system what a joke in my view it is a conflict of interests or turkeys voting for Christmas they just ain</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">t going to kick anyone out and lose their revenue stream as for char</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ity status great no shareholders just more money for pay rises pensions and bonuses.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">In my view our industry is being flooded by 6 week Scheme trained and registered “electricians” and the public are aware of this. The Scheme providers are even poaching ea</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt">ch others members to get their numbers up never mind standards.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-al